### Question 1
**Question:**
(a) State the principle of conservation of momentum. [2]
(b) Natalie attempts to retrieve a hat of mass 0.40 kg which is resting on the surface of a frozen pond. To do this, she throws a snowball, of mass 0.20 kg, at a horizontal velocity of $9.0 \text{ m s}^{-1}$ towards the hat. It hits the hat and rebounds at $2.0 \text{ m s}^{-1}$.
(i) Calculate the magnitude of the velocity of the hat after the collision. [3]
(ii) The snowball is in contact with the hat for 0.14 s. Calculate the mean force experienced by the hat in this time. [2]
(c) Natalie believes that, if the snowball stuck to the hat, the velocity of the hat would be greater than the velocity calculated in (b)(i). Without further calculation, discuss whether or not Natalie is correct. [3]

**Answer:**
(a) The vector sum of the momenta of bodies in a closed system stays constant provided there is no external/resultant force.
(b)(i) Momentum before = $0.20 \times 9.0 = 1.8 \text{ N s}$. Momentum after = $0.20 \times (-2.0) + 0.40v$. $1.8 = -0.4 + 0.40v \implies 0.40v = 2.2 \implies v = 5.5 \text{ m s}^{-1}$.
(b)(ii) Change in momentum of the hat = $0.40 \times 5.5 = 2.2 \text{ N s}$. Force = $\Delta p / \Delta t = 2.2 / 0.14 = 15.7$ N.
(c) If the snowball stuck to the hat, its decrease in momentum would be less (it doesn't rebound backwards). To conserve momentum, the increase in momentum of the hat would also be less. Therefore, the velocity increase of the hat would be lower, so Natalie is incorrect.

### Question 2
**Question:**
(a) Explain what is meant by the moment of a force about a pivot. (Five diagrammatic responses A to E are given, select the correct three). [2]
(b) Telephone engineers use an extendable arm. The pivot point has the weight of the vehicle ($2.2 \times 10^4$ N) acting 2.00 m to its left. The weight of the extendable arm ($3.0 \times 10^3$ N) acts 3.44 m to its right. The total length of the arm is 12 m, angled at 25° above the horizontal, extending equally 6m from its centre. A platform of weight $W$ acts at a horizontal distance $x$ from the pivot.
