### Question 3
**Question:**
(a) Emma uses a linear air track to determine the unknown mass, $M$, of a glider. She takes three readings of acceleration using an accelerating mass of 60 g: $0.76$, $0.71$, $0.79 \text{ m s}^{-2}$.
(i) Calculate the mean acceleration along with the absolute uncertainty in its value. [2]
(ii) Calculate the percentage uncertainty in the acceleration. [1]
(b) The 60 g mass consists of 6 slotted masses, each of $10.0 \text{ g} \pm 0.1 \text{ g}$.
(i) Determine the percentage uncertainty in the 60 g mass. [1]
(ii) Suggest how Emma could reduce the uncertainty in her value for $M$. [1]
(c) Hence determine the unknown mass, $M$, of the glider along with the absolute uncertainty in its value. [5]

**Answer:**
(a)(i) Mean acceleration = $(0.76 + 0.71 + 0.79)/3 = 0.753 \text{ m s}^{-2}$. Absolute uncertainty = $(0.79 - 0.71)/2 = \pm 0.04 \text{ m s}^{-2}$.
(a)(ii) Percentage uncertainty = $(0.04 / 0.753) \times 100\% = 5.3\%$.
(b)(i) 6 masses have an absolute uncertainty of $\pm 0.6$ g. Percentage uncertainty = $(0.6 / 60) \times 100\% = 1\%$.
(b)(ii) Increase the mass of the glider, decrease the slotted mass, measure acceleration between two light gates, or take more repeat readings.
(c) Total mass of the system = $\frac{F}{a} = \frac{60 \times 10^{-3} \times 9.81}{0.753} = 0.78$ kg.
Mass of the glider $M = 0.78 - 0.06 = 0.72$ kg.
Total percentage uncertainty = $5.3\% + 1\% = 6.3\%$.
Absolute uncertainty in the total mass = $0.78 \times 6.3\% = 0.049 \approx 0.05$ kg.
Mass of glider = $0.72 \pm 0.05$ kg.

