### Question 6
**Question:**
(a) Discuss the energy changes involved in a bungee jump over one complete jump (from the initial jump height to the bottom of the jump and back up again). [6 QER]
(b) The graph of load against extension for a rubber bungee cord is shown. Curve A shows loading, and curve B shows unloading.
(i) State which feature of the graph confirms that the rubber cord is elastic. [1]
(ii) State what happens to the molecules when the elastic band is stretched. [1]
(iii) Showing your method, use curve A to estimate the work done in producing an extension of 0.3 m. [2]
(iv) When the specimen is gradually unloaded, the curve B is different from curve A. Name this phenomenon and account for it in terms of energy. [2]

**Answer:**
(a) Before jumping, the energy is entirely gravitational potential energy (GPE). During free fall, GPE is transferred to kinetic energy (KE). When the cord begins to stretch, elastic potential energy (EPE) increases. KE initially continues to increase, but as the cord stretches further, the restoring force causes KE to decrease. At the lowest point, KE is momentarily zero, and all initial GPE has been transferred to EPE (minus thermal energy dissipated). As the jumper rebounds, EPE is transferred back into KE and GPE. The jumper does not reach the initial height because some energy is dissipated as thermal energy due to air resistance and hysteresis in the cord.
(b)(i) The unloading curve returns exactly to the origin (its original unstretched length).
(b)(ii) Work is done to straighten/untangle the polymer chains.
(b)(iii) The work done is the area under curve A up to 0.3 m. By counting squares or estimating with geometric shapes (triangles/trapeziums), the area is approximately $6.0 \pm 0.4$ J.
(b)(iv) This phenomenon is called hysteresis. It represents the difference between the energy stored during loading and the useful energy recovered during unloading; the difference is dissipated as thermal energy.

