### Question 6
**Question:**
State what is meant by ‘unpolarised light’ and describe carefully how you would determine, using a polarising filter (polaroid), whether a light source is giving out polarised or unpolarised light. [6 QER]

**Answer:**
In unpolarised light, the electric field vibrations occur in all possible directions at right angles to the direction of propagation, and the sequence of directions is random. To determine whether a light source emits polarised or unpolarised light, view the light through a polarising filter (polaroid) and slowly rotate the filter. If the light is unpolarised, the intensity (brightness) of the transmitted light will decrease compared to the source, but it will remain constant regardless of the angle of the polaroid. If the light is plane-polarised, the intensity will vary as the polaroid is rotated, reaching two points of maximum transmission and two points of complete extinction per $360^\circ$ turn.

